post_text: Beginning Monday, August 31st, there will be changes to the "Grab and Go" meal pick up times and locations. Meals will now be provided from 7:30 a.m. to 9:00 a.m. and 10:30 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. at Cromer Elementary, Killip Elementary, Kinsey Elementary, Leupp Elementary, and Thomas Elementary. There will no longer be meal pick up locations at Flagstaff High School or Sinagua Middle School. Additionally, meals will still be available via bus distribution. Please visit http://ow.ly/PnJq50BcbVx for more information.

Flagstaff High School Performing Arts
August 13 at 4:22 PM ·

**VOTING ENDS TODAY AT 5pm!

Attention Flagstaff!

Alyssa Williams, one of the rock stars that won Vans, was selected as a finalist for a new competition to have her design featured on a state license plate, which will contain the Native American Code Talkers seal she created. She has been in the lead the whole time, until the past couple of hours.

Voting ends TOMORROW at 5pm. Could you please take a moment to vote at the link below?

This is very important to her, as a Navajo young lady. She wants to be a designer once she leaves high school. All the success she has had in the past couple years could launch her into an insanely rewarding and successful career.

https://gotr.azgovernor.gov/gotr/code-talker-seal-design-contest

post_text:
Team FUSD is continuing efforts to prepare for remote learning and we understand that families have many questions regarding special education services in this new environment. To help answer your questions, we have prepared the following presentation.

The nature of special education is individualized to each student and this presentation is to best provide a general overview on how things will look during this first quarter of remote learning. The presentation has been closed caption and translated into Spanish. Both can be accessed by selecting the "CC" button in the lower right hand corner of the video.

2020 STEMmy Awards

STEM City Central premiered a video.
June 14 at 4:10 PM ·

Recognizing excellence in the areas of Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics (STEM), the eighth annual Flagstaff STEMmy Awards will be held digitally on our Facebook page on Wednesday, June 17, 2020 at 5:00 p.m.

STEM City requests nominations for candidates each spring for candidates or organizations in the areas of community support, student achievement, and exemplary teaching. A panel reviews the submissions to determine the winner of each area and winners receive $500.

Congratulations to the winners and all of the nominees!

post_text:
We Hear You. We Stand with You.

The death of George Floyd in Minneapolis, Minnesota is a tragedy that has appropriately sparked a national response to the inequities and racism that exist not only in our nation's history, but currently in our own communities. The Flagstaff Unified School District will continue to ensure all students are safe and have access to the champions and supports they need to succeed.

We understand that is our responsibility as educators to engage our students and families to inform and address issues of systemic racism. Together, there is strength, and we are committed to working side-by-side with our community to raise up kindness and inclusion.

We respect you. We honor you.

Superintendent Michael Penca on behalf of Team FUSD

post_text: On April 29, 2020, the CocoNuts FIRST Robotics Team of Coconino High School earned their 9th Regional Chairman’s Award, the most prestigious honor in FIRST. This award recognizes a team that best represents a model for others to emulate and best embodies the purpose and goals of FIRST. Two sophomore members of the CocoNuts were also honored. Noah Temprendola was named a finalist for the FIRST Dean’s List, and Oscar Landa Samano, a semifinalist. The FIRST Dean’s List honors student leaders who have led their teams and communities to increased awareness for FIRST and its mission. These students have also achieved personal technical expertise and accomplishment. Congratulations CocoNuts! Read more about the team’s accomplishments here: http://ow.ly/I7t950zxAS0

post_text:
The Flagstaff Unified School District (FUSD) Governing Board approved changes to the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year calendar. The last day for students is now scheduled on Friday, May 22, 2020. The revised schedule shifts the three (3) remaining optional make-up days, originally scheduled for May 6, 7, and 8, to the end of the school year. Those days will now be considered as school/learning days for students and work days for all FUSD team members. New content to FUSD’s Digital Learning Hub will continue to be added each week including for the week of May 18.

“The decision to modify the calendar was made with input from our families and team members,” said Superintendent Michael Penca. “By modifying the calendar, we are able to continue our established remote learning routine for the next three full weeks and then end the school year prior to Memorial Day.”

The determination to make the change followed a survey of FUSD families and team members. There were 1,575 responses to the survey with 86% of respondents favoring the change.
text:
The Flagstaff Unified School District (FUSD) Governing Board approved changes to the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year calendar. The last day for students is now scheduled on Friday, May 22, 2020. The revised schedule shifts the three (3) remaining optional make-up days, originally scheduled for May 6, 7, and 8, to the end of the school year. Those days will now be considered as school/learning days for students and work days for all FUSD team members. New content to FUSD’s Digital Learning Hub will continue to be added each week including for the week of May 18.

“The decision to modify the calendar was made with input from our families and team members,” said Superintendent Michael Penca. “By modifying the calendar, we are able to continue our established remote learning routine for the next three full weeks and then end the school year prior to Memorial Day.”

The determination to make the change followed a survey of FUSD families and team members. There were 1,575 responses to the survey with 86% of respondents favoring the change.

Congratulations to Coconino High School’s Careers through Culinary Arts Program (C-CAP) scholarship winners and top ten junior!

Deacon Wilson was named one of the top ten juniors in the state and will have many opportunities available to him in the future.

Elizabeth Wesolek and Kylee Yazzie both participated in the Dairy Council program through C-CAP. In this program, they created recipes for a cookbook that will be published by the Arizona Dairy Council. From the Dairy Council, Liz was awarded second place in the state and a $3,000 scholarship and Kylee was awarded third place in the state and a $2,000 scholarship. In addition, Liz received the Mark Tarbell scholarship for $2,500 and Kylee was awarded the Fox Restaurant Concepts Scholarship for $1,000.

Lastly, CHS senior, Mackenzie Atkins, was awarded the $1,000 Barbara Slifka Scholarship for the C-CAP Cooking For Scholarships Senior Finalist Competition.

Way to go CHS Culinary!

post_text: Congratulations to Flagstaff High School on being named as a Recognized ASCA Model Program (RAMP) by the American School Counselor Association . The RAMP designation recognizes schools that are committed to delivering an exemplary school counseling program. Honorees are awarded for aligning their program with the criteria in the ASCA National Model, a framework for a data-informed school counseling program. Since the program’s inception, more than 900 schools earned the RAMP designation. Research findings indicate fully implemented comprehensive school counseling programs are associated with a range of positive student educational and behavioral outcomes. Flagstaff High School is one of five programs that have been designated in Arizona.

post_text:
This morning Governor Doug Ducey and Superintendent of Public Instruction Kathy Hoffman announced that all public schools in Arizona will be closed through the rest of the 2019-2020 school year in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. This includes all schools and programs of the Flagstaff Unified School District (FUSD).

While we understand this decision has a significant impact on the FUSD and the greater Flagstaff community, we appreciate the clarity this decision provides and the ability to now make plans for this extended closure. The FUSD leadership team is meeting today to make additional plans in response to this new decision.

We are committed to keep you up to date on the actions FUSD is taking in accordance with this action.

For the most up to date information on COVID-19 and FUSD operations, please see www.fusd1.org/coronavirus.

Thank you for your patience in this developing and unprecedented situation.

post_text:
Thank you for your patience as we all adapt to the closure of schools in response to COVID-19. Today, and for much of this week, our focus is on supporting the over 1,300 employees of the Flagstaff Unified School District as they return from our District’s previously scheduled spring break and we establish new practices for them to work safely from home with the resources they will need to successfully provide services to students in the weeks ahead.

Teachers and school staff will be contacting students and parents/families over the next days to check-in with students and determine if they are able to access online instructional resources or if alternatives need to be planned. Our Curriculum & Instruction, administrative, and teacher teams are working together to develop an organized and meaningful model for remote learning. FUSD is committed to offering all students access to quality learning opportunities and resources no later than Monday, March 30, 2020. More details for students and parents will be sent out later this week.

More info at www.fusd1.org/coronavirus

The Flagstaff Unified School District (FUSD) believes it is important to keep our families updated regarding events that may impact our services. Our administrative team is closely monitoring information related to COVID-19 and coordinating with the Coconino County Health Department, the Arizona Department of Health, and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) where appropriate. FUSD is aware that other educational entities in the community and nationally are changing their schedules based on their particular circumstances. We do not have any changes to our current schedule at this time and look forward to our scheduled Spring Break next week - March 16 through March 20. Our commitment is to update you if this changes.

post_text:
Coconino High School Senior Mackenzie Atkins recently participated in the preliminary competition for Careers through Culinary Arts Programs or C-CAP. Mackenzie has qualified as a Senior Finalist and will be competing for scholarships on March 28th at Paradise Valley High School.

The preliminary competition consisted of competitors making two French rolled omelettes and a cucumber salad. They were judged on kitchen safety and sanitation, professionalism, knife skills, plate presentation and taste. Mackenzie was also selected based on her competition application that included a written essay and recommendations from teachers and employers.

The final competition on March 28th will consist of making Hunter's chicken with turned , sauteed potatoes and dessert crepes with pastry cream and chocolate sauce. As a part of her preparation for the final competition, the Culinary Coordinator for C-CAP AZ will be coming to CHS for a one on one cooking demonstration to teach Mackenzie the final competition recipes.
text:
Coconino High School Senior Mackenzie Atkins recently participated in the preliminary competition for Careers through Culinary Arts Programs or C-CAP. Mackenzie has qualified as a Senior Finalist and will be competing for scholarships on March 28th at Paradise Valley High School.

The preliminary competition consisted of competitors making two French rolled omelettes and a cucumber salad. They were judged on kitchen safety and sanitation, professionalism, knife skills, plate presentation and taste. Mackenzie was also selected based on her competition application that included a written essay and recommendations from teachers and employers.

The final competition on March 28th will consist of making Hunter's chicken with turned , sauteed potatoes and dessert crepes with pastry cream and chocolate sauce. As a part of her preparation for the final competition, the Culinary Coordinator for C-CAP AZ will be coming to CHS for a one on one cooking demonstration to teach Mackenzie the final competition recipes.

post_text:
The U.S. Census Bureau has started the selection process for various census positions in preparation of the 2020 Census. In December, pay rates increased across the nation and all part-time applicants will be able to maintain their federal benefits and assistance such as Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP), Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF), and Medicaid (non-MAGI) while working for the census. Positions offer competitive pay, flexible hours, paid training and weekly paychecks.

To determine the pay rate in a specific area, learn more about these positions, or apply for one of the temporary jobs, visit 2020census.gov/jobs.

December 9, 2019 at 12:59 PM · Flagstaff, AZ ·

On Saturday, December 7th, 2019, the Coconino High School CocoNuts hosted the 12th Annual Flagstaff First Lego League Tournament. This year’s challenge was “City Shaper,” in which the teams had to program their robots and compete in challenges to solve real-world problems including engineering, construction, design, and sustainability. Thirty-one teams across Northern Arizona competed to advance to the Arizona Championship at Arizona State University. shared_text:
SAFEKIDS.ORG
America’s Favorite Crossing Guard

Flagstaff Unified School District is in Flagstaff, Arizona.
November 25, 2019 at 10:01 AM · Flagstaff, AZ ·

Safe Kids Worldwide is holding a vote for “America’s Favorite Crossing Guard.” Marshall Elementary School has nominated Mr. Billy Weldon who has been volunteering at Marshall as a beloved crossing guard for 13 years strong. He is a Flagstaff favorite and decorated veteran. With all of the national awards he has received, this would be among one of his highest achievements. Mr. Billy always has a hug or high-five for all students as he greets them by name. He is immersed in Marshall’s culture and he is the reason Marshall is AZ’s first “Purple Heart Elementary School.” He volunteers because he genuinely loves the students and staff. Please help us honor his commitment, spirit, and unwavering support by giving Mr. Billy your vote! You can vote once a day until December 12th by following this link: https://www.safekids.org/crossing-guard?entry_id=186049956

post_text:
The Flagstaff High School Welding Team won Arizona Welding Thunder for the 4th year in a row! Each year, Mike Rust has students compete for a spot on this team. Students have to have high marks in all of their classes and good attendance. Our students covet a spot on this winning team.

During the competition, students have to work as a team, follow a blueprint and fabricate specific parts of the go-cart on site. They are judged on all of their welds and their ability to read and follow the blueprint.

Team members earning gold this year are: Tim Dana (senior), Jacob Sansone(junior), Kody Kelley (junior), Leroy Horney (junior), Ryan Chaffin (junior) and Lance Smith (junior). The instructor/sponsor is Mike Rust.

Congratulations to the FHS Welding Team for this achievement!

The Winter Storm Watch has officially been upgraded to a Winter Storm Warning this afternoon. The first segments start at 3 PM MST Thursday (from Flagstaff westward). Snow levels will initially be around 6500-7000 feet, but will fall through the night and into Friday.

post_text: Safe Kids Worldwide is holding a vote for “America’s Favorite Crossing Guard.” Marshall Elementary School has nominated Mr. Billy Weldon who has been volunteering at Marshall as a beloved crossing guard for 13 years strong. He is a Flagstaff favorite and decorated veteran. With all of the national awards he has received, this would be among one of his highest achievements. Mr. Billy always has a hug or high-five for all students as he greets them by name. He is immersed in Marshall’s culture and he is the reason Marshall is AZ’s first “Purple Heart Elementary School.” He volunteers because he genuinely loves the students and staff. Please help us honor his commitment, spirit, and unwavering support by giving Mr. Billy your vote! You can vote once a day until December 12th by following this link: https://www.safekids.org/crossing-guard?entry_id=186049956

At the invitation of the Havasupai Tribal Council, six Cadets from the Coconino High School JROTC Panther Battalion Color Guard traveled to Supai via helicopter to support the 2019 Veteran's Pow Wow at Havasu Creek. The Cadets opened the ceremonies by presenting the Colors with the National Anthem performed in the Blackfoot language, then provided the assembled tribal participants from all over the Western US, Canada, and Mexico with a demonstration of precision drill.

The Cadets later took part in the Circle Dance with Havasupai Veterans, hiked to Havasu Falls, and took the opportunity to enjoy the Blue-Green Waters. These experiences provided the Cadets a first-hand understanding of our rich cultural heritage, honored our Veterans, and provided a glimpse at a much different way of life than most of us live. Not to mention the thrill of flying a helicopter off the edge of the Grand Canyon and along the mighty Colorado River.

post_text: The Coconino High School JROTC Color Guard, along with veterans from the Lori Piestewa Post 80 of the American Legion, opened the 2019 Statewide Tribal Veterans Symposium on 1 November 2019 at the Twin Arrows Conference Center. The Statewide Tribal Veterans Symposium, organized by Congressman Tom O'Halleran, provided an opportunity to bring Tribal Veterans, Military Service Members, Families Members, and Service Providers together from all 22 tribes within Arizona. This was a day of honoring our Arizona Tribal Veterans as well as having the opportunity to learn how to provide services in a culturally appropriate way, and to work towards building and strengthening partnerships/relationships with Tribal Veteran agencies. The JROTC Cadets were able to be part of that greater partnership, working with veteran honor guards and learning first-hand of a significant part of our heritage.
text: The Coconino High School JROTC Color Guard, along with veterans from the Lori Piestewa Post 80 of the American Legion, opened the 2019 Statewide Tribal Veterans Symposium on 1 November 2019 at the Twin Arrows Conference Center. This was a day of honoring our Arizona Tribal Veterans as well as having the opportunity to learn how to provide services in a culturally appropriate way, and to work towards building and strengthening partnerships/relationships with Tribal Veteran agencies. The JROTC Cadets were able to be part of that greater partnership, working with veteran honor guards and learning first-hand of a significant part of our heritage.

KAFF News
October 31, 2019 at 4:27 PM ·

If you are heading to the 51st City Championship Football Game between Coconino and Flagstaff in the Skydome tomorrow (Friday), make sure come by the tailgate before heading into the Skydome. There will be games, fun, and a live remote on HITS 106. It runs from 5-7 p.m. so stop by. Also, if you are planning on going and don't have a ticket, get them early at the NAU ticket office or online.

If you can't go, don't forget we will have the game LIVE starting at 7 p.m. on KAFF Country Legends 93.5/AM 930. Coconino has qualified for the 4A state playoffs, but "COULD" get a home game in the first round with a win. A win by Flagstaff "MAY" get them in the 4A state playoffs and snap the two game winning streak by Coconino. Pack the Dome, or listen on KAFF Country Legends or online at KAFFLegends.com.
